        <mxCell id="s4_qrole7" parent="1" style="text;html=1;align=center;" value="&lt;font style=&quot;font-size:8px;color:#4527A0&quot;&gt;&lt;b&gt;q₇&lt;/b&gt; Frequency Envelope&lt;/font&gt;" vertex="1">
          <mxGeometry height="14" width="120" x="1092" y="792" as="geometry" />
        </mxCell>
        <mxCell id="s4_finding" parent="1" style="rounded=1;whiteSpace=wrap;html=1;fillColor=#FFEBEE;strokeColor=#EF5350;arcSize=6;fontSize=9;" value="&lt;font style=&quot;font-size:9px;color:#333&quot;&gt;&lt;b style=&quot;color:#B71C1C&quot;&gt;Key Finding:&lt;/b&gt; Qubit Q₆ develops numeral-density response: ⟨Z⟩ = +1.38 on &quot;5B18&quot; (numeral-dense) vs ⟨Z⟩ = −0.14 on &quot;IWN1J&quot; (letter-dense). This 1.52-unit swing (max possible = 2.0) is &lt;b&gt;emergent specialisation&lt;/b&gt; — not architecturally prescribed. It is the first reported &quot;numeral-density qubit&quot; in a VQC trained on a real-world sequence recognition task.&lt;/font&gt;" vertex="1">
          <mxGeometry height="55" width="1095" x="1180" y="738" as="geometry" />
        </mxCell>
        <mxCell id="s4_finding2" parent="1" style="text;html=1;align=left;" value="&lt;font style=&quot;font-size:8px;color:#666&quot;&gt;All 8 qubits develop distinct DC offsets and oscillation amplitudes after training (Table 11 in paper). This symmetry-breaking from the initial |0⟩⊗⁸ state is evidence that StronglyEntanglingLayers performs genuine input-conditional state engineering, analogous to CNN filter specialisation (Krizhevsky et al., 2012).&lt;/font&gt;" vertex="1">
          <mxGeometry height="30" width="1095" x="1180" y="798" as="geometry" />
        </mxCell>
