        <mxCell id="cmp_insight" parent="1" style="rounded=1;whiteSpace=wrap;html=1;fillColor=#FFEBEE;strokeColor=#EF5350;arcSize=6;fontSize=9;" value="&lt;font style=&quot;font-size:9px;color:#333&quot;&gt;&lt;b style=&quot;color:#BF360C&quot;&gt;Key Insight:&lt;/b&gt; The classical model narrowly wins (+0.5% accuracy), but this gap is attributable to 4 NISQ-era simulation effects (see Table 12 in paper): single-GPU constraint, parameter-shift gradient noise, train/test distribution mismatch, barren-plateau proximity. On real quantum hardware the inference overhead collapses and the gap is projected to close or reverse.&lt;/font&gt;" vertex="1">
          <mxGeometry height="130" width="285" x="2414" y="676" as="geometry" />
        </mxCell>
        <mxCell id="cmp_adv" parent="1" style="rounded=1;whiteSpace=wrap;html=1;fillColor=#FFFFFF;strokeColor=#9E9E9E;arcSize=6;fontSize=9;" value="&lt;font style=&quot;font-size:9px;color:#333&quot;&gt;&lt;b style=&quot;color:#2E7D32&quot;&gt;Classical Advantages:&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br&gt;• 15× faster inference (simulation)&lt;br&gt;• DataParallel across 2× T4&lt;br&gt;• Simple backprop (no param-shift)&lt;br&gt;• Mature, well-optimised tooling&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;b style=&quot;color:#C62828&quot;&gt;Classical Limitations:&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br&gt;• ℝ⁸ feature space (vs ℂ²⁵⁶)&lt;br&gt;• Linear coupling only&lt;br&gt;• No entanglement-based correlation&lt;br&gt;• No kernel advantage guarantee&lt;/font&gt;" vertex="1">
